WEBVTT

00:07.441 --> 00:08.075
‐ Previously,
on "The Purge"...

00:09.510 --> 00:10.911
‐ Every year,
the Purge gets worse.

00:10.944 --> 00:12.179
‐ [hollers]

00:12.212 --> 00:14.648
‐ More chaos in the streets,
more Jackals, and now Tommy.

00:14.681 --> 00:16.350
‐ What are you saying?
‐ It's not worth the risk.

00:16.383 --> 00:17.584
‐ I'm sorry.
‐ Turner!

00:17.618 --> 00:19.086
‐ No!
‐ Don't leave me!

00:19.119 --> 00:20.754
‐ No, no, no!
‐ Ben, what happened?

00:20.787 --> 00:22.356
‐ I Purged.

00:22.389 --> 00:24.124
[both grunt]
[hollers]

00:24.157 --> 00:27.594
‐ What happens on Purge Night
stays on Purge Night, okay?

00:27.628 --> 00:30.330
‐ Yeah, Purge Night.
‐ So who's Drew Adams?

00:30.364 --> 00:31.431
‐ [gasps]

00:31.465 --> 00:33.367
‐ You know I can't have you
tag and track someone

00:33.400 --> 00:35.035
from your private life,
so take some time off,

00:35.068 --> 00:36.036
then let it go.

00:36.069 --> 00:38.605
‐ These‐‐they belonged
to Professor Adams.

00:38.639 --> 00:41.642
Whatever she was researching,
it was important to her,

00:41.675 --> 00:43.143
so I'm just asking you
to help me.

00:43.176 --> 00:46.380
‐ The money was never supposed
to be in that bank.

00:46.413 --> 00:49.316
Trucks move the rest to a
private air strip in Overton.

00:49.349 --> 00:53.153
This is the score
to fund the rest of our lives.

00:53.186 --> 00:54.621
‐ The vast majority
of domestic Purges

00:54.655 --> 00:57.224
are committed by the spouse...

00:57.257 --> 00:59.526
but in my line of work,
cases like these,

00:59.560 --> 01:01.061
it's someone you know.

01:01.094 --> 01:04.298
[dramatic music fades
to rousing national anthem]

01:04.331 --> 01:06.400
‐ Remembrance Day
is here again,

01:06.433 --> 01:08.335
and we here at the NFFA

01:08.368 --> 01:12.139
wish a safe and happy holiday
to every citizen

01:12.172 --> 01:16.076
who has a loved one
sacrificed for the Purge.

01:16.109 --> 01:18.645
This weekend is a time
to honor and celebrate

01:18.679 --> 01:22.149
those great martyrs who gave
their lives for our country.

01:22.182 --> 01:24.551
‐ Thank you for your sacrifice.

01:24.585 --> 01:27.487
‐ Take time this holiday
to remember:

01:27.521 --> 01:29.656
there is no greater act
of service

01:29.690 --> 01:33.727
than to give your life
for our great nation.

01:33.760 --> 01:35.829
While we all know the Purge

01:35.862 --> 01:37.664
keeps our nation safe
and strong,

01:37.698 --> 01:41.301
it's not without cost.

01:41.335 --> 01:42.436
[device beeps]

01:42.469 --> 01:47.608
So today we also celebrate
the families,

01:47.641 --> 01:51.111
the mothers, fathers, sisters,

01:51.144 --> 01:54.247
and brothers who have made
the ultimate sacrifice.

01:54.281 --> 01:56.183
♪ ♪

01:56.216 --> 01:59.453
So if you see someone
wearing that yellow flower,

01:59.486 --> 02:02.522
give them a handshake, a hug.
‐ [blows]

02:02.556 --> 02:05.559
‐ Buy them a cup of coffee
to thank them

02:05.592 --> 02:07.894
for what they've given up
for our country.

02:07.928 --> 02:09.696
♪ ♪

02:09.730 --> 02:14.568
After all,
it's the American thing to do.

02:14.601 --> 02:17.604
[dramatic music]

02:17.638 --> 02:24.678
♪ ♪

02:38.458 --> 02:40.560
[knocking on door]

02:40.594 --> 02:43.563
[foreboding music]

02:43.597 --> 02:50.604
♪ ♪

03:02.182 --> 03:03.417
[pounding on door]

03:03.450 --> 03:05.252
‐ Oh...

03:05.285 --> 03:06.486
♪ ♪

03:06.520 --> 03:07.821
Who is it?

03:07.854 --> 03:10.557
‐ Darren.

03:10.590 --> 03:13.126
‐ Come in.
‐ [panting]

03:13.160 --> 03:14.695
‐ What's wrong?
Are you okay?

03:14.728 --> 03:16.763
‐ Yeah, um...

03:16.797 --> 03:19.266
Look, I only got a few minutes.

03:19.299 --> 03:22.536
I found this archived
at the university library.

03:22.569 --> 03:24.471
Professor Adams had filed it

03:24.504 --> 03:26.707
under a completely
different study.

03:26.740 --> 03:28.608
She was trying to hide it.

03:28.642 --> 03:30.944
‐ Physical copies...

03:30.977 --> 03:33.113
like the ones I found
at her place.

03:33.146 --> 03:35.415
‐ Less likely to be leaked
or hacked.

03:35.449 --> 03:37.951
‐ [sighs]
‐ These are the test subjects.

03:37.984 --> 03:41.188
No names, just numerical IDs.

03:41.221 --> 03:42.889
‐ What was she
studying them for?

03:42.923 --> 03:45.625
‐ Violence addiction.

03:45.659 --> 03:47.360
So those brain scans?

03:47.394 --> 03:49.663
They show that violent acts
can light up

03:49.696 --> 03:51.264
the pleasure centers
of the brain like a drug,

03:51.298 --> 03:52.599
especially those
in the younger generation‐‐

03:52.632 --> 03:55.535
those who grew up
with the 28th Amendment.

03:55.569 --> 03:58.238
If people could be addicted
to violence, well,

03:58.271 --> 04:00.474
then that goes against
everything the NFFA is saying

04:00.507 --> 04:02.209
about releasing rage
and all of that.

04:02.242 --> 04:04.377
‐ [sighs, stammers]
Well, uh, hold on,

04:04.411 --> 04:05.378
I've seen the data.

04:05.412 --> 04:07.314
Outside of Purge Night,

04:07.347 --> 04:09.316
violent crime is the lowest
it's ever been.

04:09.349 --> 04:12.319
‐ Right, but how much
of that data

04:12.352 --> 04:13.887
is actually manipulated
by the NFFA?

04:13.920 --> 04:14.855
‐ We have no proof.

04:14.888 --> 04:16.823
‐ Wait, wait, just‐‐
just hear me out, please.

04:16.857 --> 04:18.391
What if that data's
been falsified?

04:18.425 --> 04:20.494
Think about it:
if Professor Adams is right,

04:20.527 --> 04:21.595
well, that means the Purge

04:21.628 --> 04:23.497
could be making people
more violent.

04:23.530 --> 04:25.999
‐ Well, we don't have much
to go on, do we?

04:26.032 --> 04:27.200
These are the people
who would know more,

04:27.234 --> 04:28.201
so we should talk to them.

04:28.235 --> 04:29.136
‐ The studies are anonymous.

04:29.169 --> 04:31.671
I have no way
of contacting these people.

04:31.705 --> 04:33.240
‐ I do.

04:33.273 --> 04:35.375
Facial recognition.

04:35.408 --> 04:37.677
If they're a level G or above,

04:37.711 --> 04:40.480
we tag them,
and we can track them.

04:40.514 --> 04:42.549
‐ So you're saying
if I blow a stop sign,

04:42.582 --> 04:45.552
then that gives the NFFA reason
to watch my every move?

04:45.585 --> 04:47.788
‐ If you're within
camera range, yes.

04:47.821 --> 04:50.524
‐ Look, that‐‐

04:50.557 --> 04:51.925
that just gives the government

04:51.958 --> 04:54.628
more reason
to suppress dissent.

04:54.661 --> 04:55.929
Think about it:
they're lying about the Purge.

04:55.962 --> 04:58.365
What else
could they be covering up?

04:58.398 --> 05:00.400
That data suggests

05:00.433 --> 05:03.570
that the Purge is making people
want to kill more‐‐

05:03.603 --> 05:06.406
not just on Purge,
but every day of the year.

05:06.439 --> 05:09.609
The NFFA won't just allow
that sort of data to get out.

05:09.643 --> 05:10.777
♪ ♪

05:10.811 --> 05:14.047
Just be careful.

05:14.080 --> 05:17.017
[sinister music]

05:17.050 --> 05:20.053
[heavy metal music playing
over headphones]

05:20.086 --> 05:23.490
‐ [grunting]

05:23.523 --> 05:28.028
♪ ♪

05:28.061 --> 05:30.764
‐ Hey, Ben.

05:30.797 --> 05:31.865
‐ [hollers]

05:32.866 --> 05:33.934
[wails]

05:35.402 --> 05:36.870
‐ [grunting]

05:38.438 --> 05:41.508
[man singing indistinctly]

05:41.541 --> 05:43.777
‐ Hey, Ben!

05:43.810 --> 05:47.280
♪ ♪

05:47.314 --> 05:50.083
Come check this out.
‐ [panting]

05:50.116 --> 05:52.452
‐ The search
for the beloved berry farmer

05:52.485 --> 05:53.820
who went missing
nearly three months ago

05:53.854 --> 05:55.689
came to an end last night

05:55.722 --> 05:57.691
when police found his body
off Highway 19.

05:57.724 --> 05:58.558
‐ Babe, we really‐‐

05:58.592 --> 05:59.926
‐ Wait, this is that
missing farmer stuff

05:59.960 --> 06:00.994
you've been following.
Do you want to see?

06:01.027 --> 06:02.229
‐ After completing
their forensic examination,

06:02.262 --> 06:06.633
authorities have released
the cause of death:

06:06.666 --> 06:07.534
heatstroke.

06:07.567 --> 06:08.702
These hot summer days,

06:08.735 --> 06:11.538
residents should take
extra precautions

06:11.571 --> 06:14.040
and drink plenty of liquids.

06:14.074 --> 06:16.543
‐ That's so awful.

06:16.576 --> 06:19.045
My grandparents
used to live out that way.

06:19.079 --> 06:22.716
‐ Babe‐‐babe, I gotta run
an errand before the party.

06:22.749 --> 06:26.553
Can I meet you there?

06:26.586 --> 06:28.622
‐ Sure.

06:28.655 --> 06:30.323
[uneasy music]

06:30.357 --> 06:33.059
But, hey...

06:33.093 --> 06:36.897
this being
Remembrance Weekend and all...

06:36.930 --> 06:39.499
how are you doing
with all that Purge stuff?

06:39.532 --> 06:40.901
♪ ♪

06:40.934 --> 06:42.969
‐ Much better now.

06:43.003 --> 06:45.538
♪ ♪

06:45.572 --> 06:48.308
[Velcro rips]

06:48.341 --> 06:51.912
[drawer slides]

06:51.945 --> 06:52.712
[door closes]

06:52.746 --> 06:55.916
‐ Oh, God,
happy Remembrance Day.

06:55.949 --> 06:58.852
Susan just stopped me outside.

06:58.885 --> 07:01.855
She wants us to swing by
their barbecue today.

07:01.888 --> 07:05.025
Please don't make me go alone.

07:05.058 --> 07:06.660
‐ Babe, I'm sorry, I can't.

07:06.693 --> 07:08.628
The investigators
got us a lead.

07:09.396 --> 07:12.332
‐ On the truck?
‐ No, on the actual assassin.

07:12.365 --> 07:14.768
‐ But, wait, it was‐‐
he's just a guy

07:14.801 --> 07:16.002
who answered an ad, right?

07:16.036 --> 07:17.203
We need the person
who hired him.

07:17.237 --> 07:20.073
‐ I know, but look,
this guy lived

07:20.106 --> 07:21.675
on the street
that I grew up.

07:21.708 --> 07:23.310
That can't be a coincidence.

07:23.343 --> 07:24.277
Whoever put out the hit

07:24.311 --> 07:27.547
could be connected
to my past.

07:27.580 --> 07:28.682
‐ [sighs]
So you think someone

07:28.715 --> 07:30.750
you grew up with
could be behind this?

07:30.784 --> 07:33.520
‐ Baby, I don't know,
but the old crew might.

07:33.553 --> 07:35.522
Tonya's having
a get‐together today,

07:35.555 --> 07:37.457
and it might be good
for me to go around there

07:37.490 --> 07:38.558
and to show my face.

07:38.591 --> 07:40.393
I'm gonna give Darren a lift.

07:40.427 --> 07:41.461
Maybe I can
get some information.

07:41.494 --> 07:43.863
‐ Tonya, huh?
‐ Babe, come on, don't start.

07:43.897 --> 07:46.866
‐ I have been saying
we should look closer at her,

07:46.900 --> 07:49.970
and now the assassin
lives on her block?

07:50.003 --> 07:53.873
‐ Right, but me and Tonya‐‐
we have a lot of issues,

07:53.907 --> 07:55.542
but I know her.

07:55.575 --> 07:58.044
She is not capable
of doing anything like that.

07:58.078 --> 08:01.081
[tense music]

08:02.015 --> 08:05.585
‐ Okay, I hear you.

08:05.618 --> 08:11.524
♪ ♪

08:11.558 --> 08:14.094
‐ Mm, looks like Doug's
getting into position now.

08:16.763 --> 08:19.733
[indistinct chatter]

08:34.848 --> 08:36.950
‐ [sucks finger]

08:37.650 --> 08:38.952
Jammer's in place.

08:38.985 --> 08:40.620
‐ This thing gonna work?

08:40.653 --> 08:42.455
‐ I sure hope so.

08:42.489 --> 08:43.757
[suspenseful music]

08:43.790 --> 08:45.959
[device beeps]

08:45.992 --> 08:48.995
[static crackling]
[electricity crackles]

08:49.029 --> 08:51.097
♪ ♪

08:51.131 --> 08:53.099
‐ Somebody know
what's going on?

08:53.133 --> 08:57.771
♪ ♪

08:57.804 --> 09:00.473
‐ Well, it works.

09:00.507 --> 09:03.176
♪ ♪

09:03.209 --> 09:06.179
[indistinct chatter]

09:06.212 --> 09:11.684
♪ ♪

09:11.718 --> 09:14.754
[computer chirping, beeping]

09:36.776 --> 09:38.645
[foreboding music]

09:38.678 --> 09:41.714
[computer chirping, beeping]

09:41.748 --> 09:48.788
♪ ♪

09:50.190 --> 09:53.159
[computer beeping rapidly]

09:53.193 --> 10:00.200
♪ ♪

10:06.339 --> 10:07.240
[rousing patriotic music
playing over speakers]

10:08.408 --> 10:09.876
‐ Welcome to
Purge U. S. A. Store.

10:09.909 --> 10:13.680
This Remembrance Day,
we're proud to offer

10:13.713 --> 10:15.682
the best prices
and the greatest selection

10:15.715 --> 10:19.652
on all
your Purge Night needs.

10:19.686 --> 10:21.721
During our
Remembrance Day sale,

10:21.754 --> 10:26.059
we offer you
unmatched discounts.

10:26.092 --> 10:29.596
No credit?
No problem.

10:29.629 --> 10:33.166
From torture and maiming
to cleaning and disposal,

10:33.199 --> 10:34.601
all of our friendly,
experienced employees

10:34.634 --> 10:38.004
can answer any questions
you may have.

10:38.037 --> 10:40.106
♪ ♪

10:40.140 --> 10:42.842
‐ You have to ask them
to open it at the counter.

10:42.876 --> 10:45.245
‐ Thank you for shopping
Purge U. S. A. Store.

10:45.278 --> 10:47.847
We blow out
so you can blow 'em away.

10:47.881 --> 10:51.217
‐ These are behind glass,
but you can carry that around?

10:51.251 --> 10:53.253
♪ ♪

10:53.286 --> 10:55.288
‐ Yeah, I guess so.

10:55.321 --> 10:57.190
‐ You know how to use it?

10:57.223 --> 10:59.859
‐ Sure.

10:59.893 --> 11:02.262
You know how to use one
of those guns?

11:02.295 --> 11:05.198
‐ No, I was looking for this.

11:05.231 --> 11:08.101
‐ You like that up‐close
kind of shit, huh?

11:08.134 --> 11:10.136
‐ [laughs]

11:10.170 --> 11:13.773
‐ Dude, have you Purged before?

11:13.806 --> 11:16.042
‐ [weakly] Yeah.
‐ Yo, right on!

11:16.075 --> 11:18.611
[laughs]

11:18.645 --> 11:20.380
‐ [laughs]

11:20.413 --> 11:22.015
‐ You don't have
to whisper it, though, dude.

11:22.048 --> 11:23.516
There's nothing
to be ashamed of.

11:23.550 --> 11:27.887
♪ ♪

11:27.921 --> 11:30.623
‐ My girlfriend would kill me
if she knew I was here.

11:30.657 --> 11:32.892
‐ Yeah, my roommate is
a total dick about it, too.

11:32.926 --> 11:34.827
[metal scraping]
Ah.

11:34.861 --> 11:35.895
I'd put him on my list
for next year,

11:35.929 --> 11:39.999
but, uh, he lets me copy
his o‐chem tests, so...

11:40.033 --> 11:41.201
‐ You at Cooke?

11:41.234 --> 11:44.103
‐ Yeah, just started
my junior year.

11:44.137 --> 11:45.605
You?

11:45.638 --> 11:47.173
‐ Same.

11:47.207 --> 11:49.842
‐ Can even walk across the quad
without some anti‐Purger

11:49.876 --> 11:51.611
spouting off
some bullshit rhetoric.

11:51.644 --> 11:53.646
[items clatter]

11:53.680 --> 11:56.382
But out in the real world...

11:56.416 --> 11:59.819
there are way more people
like us than them.

11:59.852 --> 12:01.854
Trust me.

12:01.888 --> 12:06.059
♪ ♪

12:06.092 --> 12:09.262
‐ Hey, I'm headed to a party.
You wanna come?

12:09.295 --> 12:10.763
‐ No, thanks.

12:10.797 --> 12:13.700
I'm not into that whole, uh,
Remembrance Day thing.

12:13.733 --> 12:15.034
Mm‐mm.

12:15.068 --> 12:17.937
‐ Well, are you into
Remembrance Day drinking?

12:17.971 --> 12:20.039
♪ ♪

12:20.073 --> 12:21.841
‐ Yes.

12:21.874 --> 12:24.177
Yes, I am.

12:24.210 --> 12:26.145
♪ ♪

12:26.179 --> 12:29.048
[rousing pop music playing
over speakers]

12:29.082 --> 12:32.151
[indistinct chatter]

12:32.185 --> 12:34.721
♪ ♪

12:34.754 --> 12:36.956
[brooding music]

12:36.990 --> 12:39.826
[kids cheering]

12:39.859 --> 12:42.895
‐ [exhales sharply]

12:42.929 --> 12:44.330
‐ Marcus, where are you?

12:44.364 --> 12:46.332
‐ Hey, hey, hey, hey, I'm here.

12:46.366 --> 12:48.101
‐ It starts in ten minutes.

12:48.134 --> 12:50.169
‐ Wait, wait...

12:50.203 --> 12:51.404
[indistinct shouting]

12:51.437 --> 12:53.740
[stammers]
Baby, hold on, hold on.

12:53.773 --> 12:56.743
[sinister music]

12:56.776 --> 13:03.383
♪ ♪

13:03.416 --> 13:05.418
‐ Marcus?

13:05.451 --> 13:07.320
Marcus?

13:07.353 --> 13:08.988
Marcus, are you there?

13:09.022 --> 13:10.723
‐ Yep, I'm here.
‐ Hurry up.

13:10.757 --> 13:13.426
‐ Okay, I just parked.
I'm running in right now.

13:13.459 --> 13:18.765
♪ ♪

13:18.798 --> 13:21.668
[TV chattering]

13:21.701 --> 13:23.236
♪ ♪

13:23.269 --> 13:24.837
‐ Yo!
[laughs]

13:24.871 --> 13:27.140
Look who decided
to finally join us.

13:27.173 --> 13:29.742
‐ Hey, just in time.
‐ My soldier!

13:29.776 --> 13:31.077
[laughs]
‐ Papa!

13:31.110 --> 13:32.512
‐ Hey, you!

13:32.545 --> 13:35.281
What'd you do today?
‐ I was hammering nails.

13:35.315 --> 13:37.183
‐ Hammering nails?
‐ Yes.

13:37.216 --> 13:38.885
‐ Why was he hammering nails?

13:38.918 --> 13:40.453
‐ Shit, man,
like I can stop him.

13:40.486 --> 13:41.854
Tonya said it was fine.

13:41.888 --> 13:42.822
‐ I thought we were gonna have

13:42.855 --> 13:45.024
to send out a search party
for you.

13:45.058 --> 13:46.192
‐ Babe, work was just‐‐
‐ Yeah, it was crazy.

13:46.225 --> 13:47.994
Yeah, I know.
You'd think on Purge Night

13:48.027 --> 13:50.029
you could make an exception
for me, huh?

13:50.063 --> 13:52.098
Come‐‐hi.
‐ Do you think it's ready yet?

13:52.131 --> 13:53.933
‐ Let me see.
I think it's perfect.

13:53.966 --> 13:55.368
Can you start feeding
the little ones for me?

13:55.401 --> 13:57.370
And make sure they sit
in the center of the room

13:57.403 --> 13:58.705
away from the windows.
Thank you, baby.

13:58.738 --> 14:01.040
Come on, let's go.

14:01.074 --> 14:02.742
All right.

14:02.775 --> 14:05.745
[kids cheering, chattering]

14:05.778 --> 14:07.213
[computer beeps]

14:07.246 --> 14:09.415
[foreboding music]

14:09.449 --> 14:11.751
‐ Olivia Hughes.

14:11.784 --> 14:13.920
♪ ♪

14:13.953 --> 14:15.988
[elevator dings]

14:16.022 --> 14:17.757
‐ [exclaims, stammers]
Sorry.

14:17.790 --> 14:18.691
‐ Everything okay?

14:18.725 --> 14:21.527
‐ Uh, all good,
just late for something.

14:21.561 --> 14:23.830
[phones ringing]

14:23.863 --> 14:26.933
[phone ringing]

14:26.966 --> 14:28.034
♪ ♪

14:28.067 --> 14:29.736
‐ Hey, uh, I'm with family
right now.

14:29.769 --> 14:30.803
I can't really talk.

14:30.837 --> 14:33.005
‐ Darren, every person
on that list is dead

14:33.039 --> 14:35.775
except for one:
Olivia Hughes.

14:35.808 --> 14:37.777
There's no way
that's a coincidence.

14:37.810 --> 14:38.845
‐ And now?
‐ I'm going to her place now,

14:38.878 --> 14:40.980
see what I can find.
‐ Whoa, whoa, hold on.

14:41.013 --> 14:41.981
Are you sure
that's a good idea?

14:42.014 --> 14:44.417
‐ I'll be fine.
We'll talk later, okay?

14:44.450 --> 14:46.986
‐ All right, bye.

14:47.019 --> 14:50.189
‐ I‐‐I have some brandy
squirreled away.

14:50.223 --> 14:52.258
‐ We're good, Mom, thanks.

14:52.291 --> 14:54.193
Okay, let's run this plan.

14:54.227 --> 14:55.261
‐ Okay, before the sirens,

14:55.294 --> 14:57.263
we use the jammer to disable
the plane's electronics.

14:57.296 --> 14:59.098
‐ And we need a short window

14:59.132 --> 15:00.800
so they don't
activate it back up.

15:00.833 --> 15:02.135
‐ Ten minutes?
‐ Yeah, that's good.

15:02.168 --> 15:03.302
How you doing
on the guns and the gear?

15:03.336 --> 15:04.137
Can you get us on the tarmac?

15:04.170 --> 15:05.037
‐ Two weeks ago,
an old buddy from SWAT

15:05.071 --> 15:07.206
gave me a good deal
on an armored Humvee.

15:07.240 --> 15:09.809
The airport's perimeter
has one weak link.

15:09.842 --> 15:11.544
It's a 12‐feet
reinforced chain link.

15:11.577 --> 15:13.513
Just enough to punch
an armored Humvee through.

15:13.546 --> 15:16.015
‐ You know, we've still got
one major problem:

15:16.048 --> 15:17.984
how are we gonna get the jammer
on the airplane?

15:18.017 --> 15:23.122
♪ ♪

15:23.156 --> 15:25.591
[mellow blues music
playing over speakers]

15:25.625 --> 15:28.294
[indistinct chatter]

15:28.327 --> 15:29.629
‐ Hey, hey, young man.
‐ How are you, sir?

15:29.662 --> 15:30.463
‐ You want some, baby?

15:30.496 --> 15:32.632
‐ Please.

15:32.665 --> 15:33.800
‐ Hey, Mama.

15:33.833 --> 15:35.701
‐ Hi, go eat, please.
‐ Did you save me a plate?

15:35.735 --> 15:37.870
‐ Yes, six, six.

15:37.904 --> 15:40.206
‐ Stop it!
‐ Ooh, that's spicy!

15:40.239 --> 15:42.575
‐ Marcus, you still like
your beans fried

15:42.608 --> 15:44.210
and your chicken without skin?

15:44.243 --> 15:46.746
‐ Hey, Tonya.
‐ [laughs]

15:46.779 --> 15:48.648
‐ How you doing?

15:48.681 --> 15:49.982
‐ It's been a minute.

15:50.016 --> 15:52.985
‐ Yeah, it's been a while.

15:53.019 --> 15:54.420
Thank you.
‐ Mm‐hmm.

15:54.454 --> 15:56.656
[indistinct chatter]

15:56.689 --> 16:01.394
‐ Um, just came to see
how everybody was doing.

16:01.427 --> 16:02.361
‐ Yeah.

16:02.395 --> 16:06.399
‐ I, um‐‐I heard
you're killing it.

16:06.432 --> 16:07.500
‐ [laughs]

16:07.533 --> 16:09.302
‐ Got the graduation rate
way up there this year.

16:09.335 --> 16:12.238
‐ You saw that, huh?
‐ Of course.

16:12.271 --> 16:14.907
Yeah.
‐ It's been good.

16:14.941 --> 16:16.943
And it's been bad.
[sighs]

16:16.976 --> 16:20.112
We had a rough Purge.

16:20.146 --> 16:22.281
We lost Noah.

16:22.315 --> 16:25.117
‐ [sighs]
I grew up with him.

16:25.151 --> 16:27.553
Tonya, why you didn't call me?

16:27.587 --> 16:29.956
‐ I just figured you were busy.

16:29.989 --> 16:33.092
[indistinct chatter, cheering]

16:33.125 --> 16:36.529
Enjoy your food, okay?

16:36.562 --> 16:41.100
♪ ♪

16:41.133 --> 16:44.103
[foreboding music]

16:44.136 --> 16:51.177
♪ ♪

16:59.252 --> 17:01.287
[all gasp]
[indistinct chatter]

17:01.320 --> 17:02.388
‐ All right.

17:02.421 --> 17:05.958
Everybody,
just get this light on.

17:05.992 --> 17:07.627
‐ All right.
‐ Hold on.

17:07.660 --> 17:10.429
Everybody just be cool.

17:10.463 --> 17:12.231
‐ It's no power.
‐ Can I see that?

17:12.265 --> 17:13.032
‐ All right,
it might just be‐‐

17:13.065 --> 17:14.333
‐ Will you hand me
that flashlight?

17:14.367 --> 17:16.235
‐ Here you go.
All right.

17:16.269 --> 17:18.604
‐ Okay.

17:18.638 --> 17:21.274
Everybody stay still.

17:21.307 --> 17:23.476
Everybody's good.
[glass shatters]

17:23.509 --> 17:24.810
‐ [screams]
‐ Hey, everybody move!

17:24.844 --> 17:26.312
Away, away from the windows!
Come on.

17:26.345 --> 17:29.749
Come along, come along.
‐ Move the kids!

17:29.782 --> 17:31.450
‐ Get away from the door.
Everybody stay together.

17:31.484 --> 17:33.619
[glass continues shattering]

17:33.653 --> 17:35.655
‐ Mom, it's all right.
‐ Shh.

17:35.688 --> 17:38.124
[power tool whirring]

17:38.157 --> 17:41.093
[people screaming]

17:41.127 --> 17:46.265
♪ ♪

17:46.299 --> 17:48.067
‐ Go!
Everybody get back!

17:48.100 --> 17:50.469
[indistinct shouting]

17:50.503 --> 17:53.105
♪ ♪

17:53.139 --> 17:56.375
‐ Get back behind the table!
Move! Move! Move!

17:56.409 --> 17:58.711
[chainsaw whirring]

17:58.744 --> 18:03.249
♪ ♪

18:07.787 --> 18:08.054
[tense music]

18:10.556 --> 18:12.124
‐ Everybody okay?

18:12.158 --> 18:13.125
‐ Yeah, Ma.
‐ Yeah, yeah.

18:13.159 --> 18:17.163
♪ ♪

18:17.196 --> 18:18.731
‐ Drop your guns!
‐ [quavers]

18:18.764 --> 18:19.966
Okay.
[groans]

18:19.999 --> 18:22.134
‐ This fucker distracted us.
‐ Okay.

18:22.168 --> 18:23.035
‐ He must have come
through the back windows.

18:23.069 --> 18:25.471
‐ Stay right here.
Go, go, go.

18:25.504 --> 18:27.139
‐ Everybody just‐‐
just stay back!

18:27.173 --> 18:30.309
‐ Listen, I'm telling you.
You so much as scratch‐‐

18:30.343 --> 18:32.178
‐ Marcus, stop.
‐ Drop your guns!

18:32.211 --> 18:35.648
‐ All of you
do what the boy says, okay?

18:35.681 --> 18:38.084
Marcus, Marcus!

18:38.117 --> 18:41.220
Put it down.
Put it down.

18:41.253 --> 18:44.590
Now listen to me, Eli...

18:44.624 --> 18:46.759
‐ Shut up.
You don't know me.

18:46.792 --> 18:48.294
‐ Eli Coleman.

18:48.327 --> 18:50.029
I could pick out your voice

18:50.062 --> 18:51.631
across a schoolyard
of screaming kids

18:51.664 --> 18:54.667
and I recognize
your Air Force 1s, okay?

18:54.700 --> 18:56.736
I know what this is about.
‐ You don't know shit.

18:56.769 --> 18:58.237
‐ This is 'cause
I called you out‐‐

18:58.270 --> 19:00.239
‐ Shut the fuck up!

19:00.272 --> 19:02.441
You embarrassed me
in front of the whole school!

19:02.475 --> 19:04.043
‐ Hey, hey, hey, hey.

19:04.076 --> 19:05.678
Hey, I've been this angry, son.

19:05.711 --> 19:07.680
I know what you're feeling,
but this?

19:07.713 --> 19:09.682
This is not the way.
All right?

19:09.715 --> 19:12.518
‐ It's Eli?

19:12.551 --> 19:13.953
Listen, whoever told you

19:13.986 --> 19:17.056
that Purging gets you
what you want, they lied.

19:17.089 --> 19:18.691
‐ It's the law.

19:18.724 --> 19:21.193
‐ Hey, the people in this room
could help you

19:21.227 --> 19:23.863
more than any law ever could.

19:23.896 --> 19:26.198
‐ You don't have to do this.

19:26.232 --> 19:27.700
[suspenseful music]

19:27.733 --> 19:30.236
‐ You hear me?

19:30.269 --> 19:32.805
You with me?
[gasps, sighs]

19:32.838 --> 19:34.807
‐ You don't have to do this.

19:34.840 --> 19:37.877
Please, give me that.
Give it to me.

19:37.910 --> 19:40.112
‐ Yeah, hey, hey.

19:40.146 --> 19:42.081
You've got family here, okay?

19:42.114 --> 19:46.452
That's not something
you just throw away, all right?

19:46.485 --> 19:49.588
♪ ♪

19:49.622 --> 19:52.158
Okay.

19:52.191 --> 19:54.794
Okay, okay, okay.

19:54.827 --> 19:57.663
[indistinct chatter]

19:57.697 --> 20:00.666
[no audible dialogue]

20:00.700 --> 20:06.572
♪ ♪

20:07.773 --> 20:10.176
[foreboding music]

20:10.209 --> 20:11.844
[keys jingling]

20:11.877 --> 20:14.480
♪ ♪

20:14.513 --> 20:16.816
[tires squealing]

20:16.849 --> 20:20.753
♪ ♪

20:20.786 --> 20:22.755
‐ Hey, what's good, Andre?

20:22.788 --> 20:24.423
‐ Hey, now.

20:24.457 --> 20:26.659
‐ Yo.

20:26.692 --> 20:28.627
‐ Hey.

20:28.661 --> 20:30.296
You think
I don't know?

20:30.329 --> 20:32.598
‐ What are you talking about?
‐ You son of a bitch.

20:32.631 --> 20:34.366
Huh?
‐ Marcus, what are you doing?

20:34.400 --> 20:36.135
‐ Marcus!
‐ Hey, hey, hey!

20:36.168 --> 20:37.503
‐ Marcus!
‐ Dad, Dad!

20:37.536 --> 20:38.771
‐ Marcus!
‐ Huh?

20:38.804 --> 20:39.672
‐ Let go of him!
‐ Stop it!

20:39.705 --> 20:40.906
[overlapping shouting]
‐ Marcus, stop!

20:40.940 --> 20:41.974
‐ You tried to run me down!
‐ What are you talking about?

20:42.007 --> 20:44.276
‐ Is that
why you're here today?

20:44.310 --> 20:46.378
‐ No, he tried to Purge me!
‐ Whoa, stop‐‐

20:46.412 --> 20:47.313
‐ Hold on, hold on.
No, he didn't.

20:47.346 --> 20:48.280
Look‐‐look, look‐‐
‐ What's that?

20:48.314 --> 20:49.348
‐ It's nothing.
I don't know.

20:49.381 --> 20:50.416
‐ The Jamaican flag right there
and the roof rack

20:50.449 --> 20:51.350
with the spotlights!

20:51.383 --> 20:55.354
You didn't mention any of that,
did you?

20:55.387 --> 20:57.923
I can't believe you came here
today for that.

20:57.957 --> 20:59.658
‐ Come here.
Give me a second.

20:59.692 --> 21:01.861
‐ I came here...

21:01.894 --> 21:03.863
♪ ♪

21:03.896 --> 21:05.464
I'm sorry.

21:05.498 --> 21:07.533
‐ Nice to see you, too, Marcus.

21:07.566 --> 21:10.302
‐ I said I'm sorry.

21:10.336 --> 21:11.537
‐ Out of control, man.

21:11.570 --> 21:14.640
‐ You go
clean yourself up, okay?

21:14.673 --> 21:16.375
[tense music]

21:16.408 --> 21:17.409
‐ Shame on these two.

21:17.443 --> 21:20.279
‐ All right, y'all, it's fine.
I'm sorry, y'all.

21:20.312 --> 21:22.515
Go on, we good.

21:22.548 --> 21:24.250
‐ Even if we could
get access,

21:24.283 --> 21:26.252
tampering with an aircraft
is a level R crime.

21:26.285 --> 21:27.686
‐ But what if we don't put it
on a plane?

21:27.720 --> 21:28.821
We put it in the money.

21:28.854 --> 21:29.688
‐ We'd have to get it
in the vault

21:29.722 --> 21:30.823
before they loaded it up.

21:30.856 --> 21:32.324
‐ Okay, do one of us
have enough time

21:32.358 --> 21:33.159
to get a job at the bank?

21:33.192 --> 21:34.160
‐ New employees
wouldn't have access.

21:34.193 --> 21:35.227
‐ Has to be another way in.

21:35.261 --> 21:36.662
Look, I told my family
this would be the last time.

21:36.695 --> 21:40.332
Gotta make it count.

21:40.366 --> 21:41.834
‐ Tommy?

21:41.867 --> 21:43.836
‐ Yeah, banks were
always Tommy's job.

21:43.869 --> 21:44.937
‐ And he spent all those years

21:44.970 --> 21:47.206
building those
personal connections.

21:47.239 --> 21:49.441
‐ Then we need Tommy.

21:49.475 --> 21:51.410
What are we gonna do?

21:51.443 --> 21:54.413
‐ Say no to the Purge?
‐ Mm‐hmm.

21:54.446 --> 21:56.248
‐ Cheers.
‐ Hey, guys.

21:56.282 --> 21:58.517
‐ Hey.
‐ Say no to the Purge?

21:58.551 --> 21:59.418
‐ Cool.

21:59.451 --> 22:01.587
[pin clatters]

22:01.620 --> 22:03.856
‐ It's a party,
not a peace march.

22:03.889 --> 22:05.958
‐ Have fun on the wrong side
of history, assholes.

22:05.991 --> 22:07.960
[peppy pop music
playing over speakers]

22:07.993 --> 22:10.963
‐ Hi, what was all that?

22:10.996 --> 22:12.798
‐ What's up, Sad Town?

22:12.832 --> 22:17.436
You are too soft, Benny.
[laughs]

22:17.469 --> 22:18.737
♪ ♪

22:18.771 --> 22:21.240
‐ God, that guy is being
a real dick today.

22:21.273 --> 22:22.174
‐ Hey, Kelen.

22:22.208 --> 22:25.277
‐ Can't believe you're friends
with that guy.

22:25.311 --> 22:27.713
‐ I probably shouldn't be.

22:27.746 --> 22:29.782
He ditched me on Purge Night.
‐ Wait, what?

22:29.815 --> 22:32.284
‐ Yeah, left me for dead.

22:32.318 --> 22:36.322
‐ Dude, if he did that to me,
I'd Purge him.

22:36.355 --> 22:37.556
‐ Someone you know personally?

22:37.590 --> 22:39.558
‐ Best thing I ever did
was make a list

22:39.592 --> 22:41.493
of all the people
who made my life miserable.

22:41.527 --> 22:43.596
‐ And you Purged them?
‐ Some.

22:43.629 --> 22:47.299
When an asshole pisses me off,
I start making my plan.

22:47.333 --> 22:49.235
Watching my targets all year,

22:49.268 --> 22:50.569
just knowing how easy
it would be

22:50.603 --> 22:52.938
for me to end them
keeps me sane.

22:52.972 --> 22:54.740
♪ ♪

22:54.773 --> 22:57.543
Come on, imagine choking
that guy out, Ben.

22:57.576 --> 22:59.411
Seeing the look on his face
when he figures out

22:59.445 --> 23:01.013
he never should have
fucked with you.

23:01.046 --> 23:04.416
[distorted audio]

23:04.450 --> 23:06.919
♪ ♪

23:06.952 --> 23:08.621
‐ You make a good point.

23:08.654 --> 23:09.889
♪ ♪

23:11.323 --> 23:14.326
[passing engine rumbling]

23:15.561 --> 23:18.597
[uneasy whistling]

23:18.631 --> 23:25.638
♪ ♪

23:30.643 --> 23:33.646
[distant chatter]

23:56.669 --> 23:58.737
‐ Hey!
‐ [gasps]

23:58.771 --> 24:00.406
‐ The hell you think
you're doing?

24:00.439 --> 24:02.608
‐ Oh, I'm looking for Olivia.

24:02.641 --> 24:05.411
‐ So am I.
Her rent's late.

24:05.444 --> 24:07.713
‐ When was the last time
you saw her?

24:07.746 --> 24:10.849
‐ I almost never see her.
She works nights.

24:12.751 --> 24:14.553
‐ I work for the NFFA.

24:14.586 --> 24:16.488
I need to
get into her apartment.

24:16.522 --> 24:19.591
‐ Look, whatever she's into,
I‐‐I'm not part of it.

24:19.625 --> 24:22.361
I'm happy to help the NFFA.

24:22.394 --> 24:25.497
[door opens]
[keys jingling]

24:28.200 --> 24:30.402
‐ Olivia?

24:30.436 --> 24:33.405
[sinister music]

24:33.439 --> 24:40.479
♪ ♪

25:09.675 --> 25:12.644
[fly buzzing]

25:12.678 --> 25:18.217
♪ ♪

25:18.250 --> 25:21.220
[dramatic music]

25:21.253 --> 25:24.123
♪ ♪

25:28.627 --> 25:29.328
‐ So you think
someone did this to her?

25:30.195 --> 25:32.664
‐ I'm telling you,
the latch was broken.

25:32.698 --> 25:33.799
‐ Haven't seen a B & E
for six years,

25:33.832 --> 25:34.900
let alone a murder.

25:34.933 --> 25:36.235
‐ The window was pried open.
Go look for yourself.

25:36.268 --> 25:37.569
‐ How did you get
into the apartment?

25:37.603 --> 25:42.608
‐ [stammers]
Uh, the manager let me in.

25:42.641 --> 25:45.711
Uh, we have cameras
on Benton and Marine.

25:45.744 --> 25:47.613
They might have
caught something.

25:47.646 --> 25:50.949
I'll check the footage
when I get back to the office.

25:50.983 --> 25:54.787
‐ Look, here's my card.

25:54.820 --> 25:57.056
Feel free to send me whatever
you can find on camera.

25:57.089 --> 25:59.658
‐ Yeah, uh, thank you.

25:59.691 --> 26:02.694
[radio chatter]

26:04.096 --> 26:05.964
[buzzer buzzing]

26:05.998 --> 26:08.967
[indistinct chatter]
[metal jingling]

26:14.039 --> 26:15.908
[buzzer buzzes]

26:15.941 --> 26:18.844
[tense music]

26:18.877 --> 26:20.979
♪ ♪

26:21.013 --> 26:23.749
[buzzer buzzes]

26:23.782 --> 26:27.186
♪ ♪

26:27.219 --> 26:29.655
[buzzer buzzes]

26:29.688 --> 26:31.890
♪ ♪

26:31.924 --> 26:34.893
[warm music]

26:34.927 --> 26:41.967
♪ ♪

26:42.201 --> 26:43.669
‐ Hey, thank you.

26:43.702 --> 26:45.170
Tell Aaron I said hey, okay?
‐ No problem.

26:45.204 --> 26:48.507
Five minutes,
and the camera's back on.

26:48.540 --> 26:50.843
[buzzer buzzes]

26:50.876 --> 26:52.077
‐ [laughs]
‐ [sighs]

26:52.111 --> 26:54.346
‐ How the hell did you
arrange this?

26:54.379 --> 26:56.348
‐ Oh, I've still got
a few friends left over

26:56.381 --> 26:57.382
from the days on the force.

26:57.416 --> 26:58.484
‐ Oh, "friends."

26:58.517 --> 27:00.752
The kind of friends
who accept large cash bribes?

27:00.786 --> 27:04.556
‐ Those are the ones
that stick around.

27:04.590 --> 27:06.859
It's good to see you.

27:06.892 --> 27:09.928
I've been checking in
on Lisa and the baby.

27:09.962 --> 27:11.964
They're good.

27:11.997 --> 27:14.066
♪ ♪

27:14.099 --> 27:16.602
‐ So...

27:16.635 --> 27:19.071
what's the job?

27:19.104 --> 27:21.874
Come on, Ryan,
you don't have to feel guilty.

27:21.907 --> 27:23.909
I know you're not gonna risk
showing your face

27:23.942 --> 27:25.978
to a bunch of prison guards
just to say hi.

27:26.011 --> 27:28.981
‐ You know it's not
always about the money, right?

27:29.014 --> 27:30.749
‐ I know.

27:30.782 --> 27:33.785
‐ I need a big score...

27:33.819 --> 27:36.155
something to get Sara and Doug
out of this business.

27:36.188 --> 27:37.823
‐ How big?

27:37.856 --> 27:40.025
‐ $100 million.

27:40.058 --> 27:41.927
‐ That's "get the fuck out
of this country" kind of money.

27:41.960 --> 27:44.763
‐ That's the idea...

27:44.796 --> 27:46.098
but we're stuck.

27:46.131 --> 27:49.034
‐ Of course you are.
You don't have me.

27:49.067 --> 27:52.070
‐ I need a bank employee
with vault access.

27:52.104 --> 27:55.741
♪ ♪

27:55.774 --> 27:58.944
[metal clangs]

27:58.977 --> 28:01.713
‐ I know a guy...

28:01.747 --> 28:02.915
Carl.

28:02.948 --> 28:05.817
He might be able to get you in
at Southern, but...

28:05.851 --> 28:08.921
[sighs]
Real loudmouth,

28:08.954 --> 28:11.623
and he can be erratic.

28:11.657 --> 28:13.892
[keys jangling, metal clangs]

28:13.926 --> 28:14.793
‐ Plan changed.

28:14.826 --> 28:16.728
I need to walk you out of here
right now.

28:16.762 --> 28:19.765
‐ Shit, hey.
‐ Go.

28:19.798 --> 28:21.300
Please tell me
you put a file in here,

28:21.333 --> 28:23.335
or at least some porn.

28:23.368 --> 28:25.103
‐ It's nothing that's gonna
get you in trouble,

28:25.137 --> 28:27.873
but I figured you could
use some good reading.

28:27.906 --> 28:31.443
[buzzer buzzes]

28:31.476 --> 28:33.779
[door clangs]

28:33.812 --> 28:36.381
♪ ♪

28:36.415 --> 28:38.150
[indistinct chatter]

28:38.183 --> 28:40.919
[echoing chatter, laughter]

28:42.054 --> 28:44.223
‐ Yeah, and it's even better
in person.

28:44.256 --> 28:47.793
It's the Garden District.

28:47.826 --> 28:50.529
No, stop.

28:50.562 --> 28:51.597
[both laugh]

28:51.630 --> 28:55.801
It's pricey, but once my
attending salary kicks in,

28:55.834 --> 28:56.735
everything is gonna change.

28:56.768 --> 28:59.304
[tender, melancholy music]

28:59.338 --> 29:01.206
‐ What if I don't want it
to change?

29:01.240 --> 29:04.042
‐ We gotta be safe.

29:04.076 --> 29:06.345
‐ More bedrooms
and a view of the river.

29:06.378 --> 29:09.915
That's not gonna
make us safe, baby.

29:09.948 --> 29:11.817
‐ I had to kill someone, Tonya.

29:11.850 --> 29:13.085
Every year, it's getting worse
around here.

29:13.118 --> 29:17.055
A kid put a knife
to your neck, right?

29:17.089 --> 29:18.924
And he could have killed you.

29:18.957 --> 29:20.993
‐ But he didn't, okay?

29:21.026 --> 29:22.995
And that's because
we stood together.

29:23.028 --> 29:25.097
'Cause all these people here‐‐
that's our community.

29:25.130 --> 29:26.298
That matters.

29:26.331 --> 29:28.367
‐ Right, and they always
will be.

29:28.400 --> 29:29.468
Just‐‐
‐ I'm sorry.

29:29.501 --> 29:32.004
I'm sorry, this just‐‐
it's not...

29:32.037 --> 29:33.772
it's just not what I want.

29:33.805 --> 29:35.907
‐ Okay.

29:35.941 --> 29:39.344
All right, so we find a place
that you like.

29:39.378 --> 29:42.180
♪ ♪

29:42.214 --> 29:44.716
‐ I'm not just talking
about the house.

29:44.750 --> 29:50.856
♪ ♪

29:50.889 --> 29:53.358
That's a hell
of a homecoming, there, Marcus.

29:53.392 --> 29:54.793
‐ Yeah, sorry.

29:54.826 --> 29:57.095
‐ Yeah.

29:57.129 --> 30:00.866
‐ Look, somebody hired
an assassin to Purge me.

30:00.899 --> 30:02.401
‐ What? Come here.

30:02.434 --> 30:04.102
Come here.

30:04.136 --> 30:06.538
Why didn't you tell me?

30:06.571 --> 30:08.373
‐ Look, whoever did
tried to run me down

30:08.407 --> 30:09.775
in a truck just like Andre's.

30:09.808 --> 30:11.643
‐ There are a thousand assholes
out there with that truck.

30:11.677 --> 30:14.212
‐ Do you know that
the assassin lived

30:14.246 --> 30:15.981
a few blocks away from here?

30:16.014 --> 30:18.283
And that is not random.

30:18.317 --> 30:20.552
Let me show you this.

30:20.585 --> 30:23.055
Do you know him?

30:23.088 --> 30:25.824
‐ No, I've never
seen him before.

30:25.857 --> 30:27.326
But a while back,
there was some guy

30:27.359 --> 30:30.395
that came around
asking about you.

30:30.429 --> 30:32.331
‐ "A while back"‐‐
like, when, exactly?

30:32.364 --> 30:35.334
‐ Last summer, like,
way before Purge.

30:35.367 --> 30:39.838
‐ So can you‐‐you remember?
Can you describe him?

30:39.871 --> 30:41.440
‐ ♪ I have something
to tell you ♪

30:41.473 --> 30:43.342
♪ Something that
you won't like ♪

30:43.375 --> 30:45.243
♪ Something that
you won't like ♪

30:45.277 --> 30:47.245
♪ Something that
you won't like ♪

30:47.279 --> 30:50.248
[indistinct chatter]

30:50.282 --> 30:57.289
♪ ♪

30:58.957 --> 31:01.927
‐ Stop!
Jerk, get off of me.

31:01.960 --> 31:03.428
I said leave me alone!

31:03.462 --> 31:10.402
♪ ♪

31:10.435 --> 31:13.438
[music, chatter echoing]

31:13.472 --> 31:16.441
[dark music]

31:16.475 --> 31:23.482
♪ ♪

31:28.053 --> 31:29.521
‐ I'm sorry.
‐ No, don't leave me!

31:29.554 --> 31:31.890
[distorted audio]

31:31.923 --> 31:38.096
♪ ♪

31:42.367 --> 31:43.168
[muffled pop music playing
over speakers]

31:45.303 --> 31:48.273
[sinister music]

31:48.306 --> 31:54.713
♪ ♪

31:54.746 --> 31:57.816
‐ [weeping softly]

31:57.849 --> 32:04.856
♪ ♪

32:11.530 --> 32:13.832
[sighs]
Door's closed for a reason.

32:13.865 --> 32:15.567
[sniffles]

32:15.600 --> 32:18.236
I hate this
stupid fucking day, man.

32:18.270 --> 32:20.172
♪ ♪

32:20.205 --> 32:23.175
[weeping softly]

32:23.208 --> 32:29.581
♪ ♪

32:29.614 --> 32:31.316
I got this today.

32:31.349 --> 32:34.352
It's my brother.

32:34.386 --> 32:37.422
I guess he had me down
as his emergency contact.

32:37.456 --> 32:39.357
‐ Why didn't you tell me
he got Purged?

32:39.391 --> 32:41.593
‐ Because...

32:41.626 --> 32:43.895
I left you to die.

32:43.929 --> 32:47.699
I keep thinking, what if
he was out with friends,

32:47.732 --> 32:50.635
and what if they abandoned him?

32:50.669 --> 32:52.704
[somber music]

32:52.737 --> 32:54.506
God.

32:54.539 --> 32:56.541
[sighs]

32:56.575 --> 32:58.677
♪ ♪

32:58.710 --> 33:02.514
I am so fucking sorry, Ben.

33:02.547 --> 33:05.917
We shouldn't have gone out
that night.

33:05.951 --> 33:08.186
I shouldn't have left you
like that.

33:08.220 --> 33:11.690
♪ ♪

33:11.723 --> 33:14.793
‐ I lived.
‐ [sniffling]

33:14.826 --> 33:18.396
♪ ♪

33:18.430 --> 33:21.366
What is that?

33:21.399 --> 33:24.736
‐ Oh, uh, I was
cutting limes downstairs.

33:24.769 --> 33:26.972
‐ With a hunting knife?

33:27.005 --> 33:29.441
‐ Is that weird?

33:29.474 --> 33:31.276
‐ [laughs]

33:31.309 --> 33:33.945
So weird.

33:33.979 --> 33:36.615
Come on, I'll show you
how to make a drink

33:36.648 --> 33:38.250
like a normal person.

33:38.283 --> 33:40.685
‐ Yeah, I'll be down.

33:40.719 --> 33:42.320
‐ You're gonna miss the party.
‐ I said I'll be down.

33:42.354 --> 33:43.688
Jesus.

33:48.426 --> 33:50.962
‐ [sighs]
Hey.

33:50.996 --> 33:53.765
‐ Hey.

33:55.700 --> 33:58.603
‐ So, how'd it go?

33:58.637 --> 34:02.574
‐ Um, this guy came
to Tonya's house last August...

34:03.642 --> 34:05.277
Asking lots of questions.

34:05.310 --> 34:07.779
‐ Did she know who he was?

34:07.812 --> 34:10.482
‐ [sighs]
She had no idea.

34:10.515 --> 34:13.585
[tense music]

34:13.618 --> 34:16.421
I guess he was, um, tall,
brown hair.

34:16.454 --> 34:17.822
♪ ♪

34:17.856 --> 34:19.925
Not much to go on.

34:19.958 --> 34:21.826
♪ ♪

34:21.860 --> 34:25.564
[sighs, clicks tongue]
This fucks with my timeline.

34:25.597 --> 34:28.366
[sighs]

34:28.400 --> 34:29.901
♪ ♪

34:29.935 --> 34:31.436
I mean...
[clears throat]

34:31.469 --> 34:34.873
Most everyone
that we're looking into

34:34.906 --> 34:37.776
I had contact with
more recently.

34:37.809 --> 34:40.712
I mean, who the fuck
did I piss off last summer?

34:40.745 --> 34:44.683
Anyway, I'm going to tear down
the suspect board, start again,

34:44.716 --> 34:46.818
so don't wait up.

34:46.851 --> 34:49.087
‐ Okay.
‐ I'm gonna be a while.

34:49.120 --> 34:56.328
♪ ♪

35:02.500 --> 35:04.302
‐ [scoffs]

35:04.336 --> 35:05.604
♪ ♪

35:05.637 --> 35:09.908
[sighs]

35:09.941 --> 35:12.911
[sinister music]

35:12.944 --> 35:19.985
♪ ♪

35:21.519 --> 35:23.388
‐ Say no to the Purge?

35:23.421 --> 35:25.490
♪ ♪

35:25.523 --> 35:27.158
‐ [screams]
‐ [hollers]

35:27.192 --> 35:29.728
‐ Have fun on the wrong side
of history, assholes.

35:29.761 --> 35:36.768
♪ ♪

35:51.716 --> 35:54.919
[computer chirps]
[keys tapping]

35:54.953 --> 35:57.922
[tense music]

35:57.956 --> 36:04.996
♪ ♪

36:18.610 --> 36:21.212
[computer chimes]

36:21.246 --> 36:25.684
♪ ♪

36:29.921 --> 36:30.622
[muffled heavy music
over speakers]

36:33.525 --> 36:40.565
♪ ♪

36:46.838 --> 36:49.808
‐ Tommy's friend?
[laughs]

36:49.841 --> 36:51.076
Crazy dude, that guy.

36:51.109 --> 36:53.111
He's always up
for a‐‐a good time.

36:53.144 --> 36:55.246
It's too bad
he's, uh, in the clink,

36:55.280 --> 36:57.615
'cause, uh, nothing good
ever happens in there,

36:57.649 --> 37:00.118
am I right?

37:00.151 --> 37:02.620
So...

37:02.654 --> 37:07.358
are you, like, planning
a heist on Purge Night?

37:07.392 --> 37:09.260
‐ No.

37:09.294 --> 37:10.261
‐ What, then?

37:10.295 --> 37:11.262
Because I am done

37:11.296 --> 37:13.765
with Tommy's baby shit
little freelance gigs.

37:13.798 --> 37:16.267
I want in on a score.

37:16.301 --> 37:17.168
‐ Can you get us to the vaults

37:17.202 --> 37:19.804
that get loaded
onto the airplanes?

37:19.838 --> 37:20.972
‐ How did you hear about those?

37:21.005 --> 37:23.775
‐ And I need access
before Purge,

37:23.808 --> 37:27.846
and it needs to be legal‐‐
at least, as legal as possible.

37:27.879 --> 37:29.714
‐ You do know
how to dream big.

37:29.748 --> 37:32.383
‐ Can you do it?
‐ [laughs]

37:32.417 --> 37:35.153
Probably not.

37:35.186 --> 37:37.722
[suspenseful music]

37:37.756 --> 37:38.957
‐ You get us
where we need to be

37:38.990 --> 37:41.159
and I'll cut you in
on the score.

37:41.192 --> 37:43.728
‐ [laughs softly]

37:43.762 --> 37:45.830
That is the motivation I like.

37:45.864 --> 37:48.299
I'm‐‐I'm on it.

37:48.333 --> 37:49.434
Okay...
[laughs]

37:49.467 --> 37:52.337
Man, you should really‐‐
you should really come in here.

37:52.370 --> 37:55.373
[laughs]

37:55.406 --> 37:57.175
They make a mean gin fizz,

37:57.208 --> 37:58.309
and if you show them
one of these,

37:58.343 --> 37:59.844
you get a free lap dance.

37:59.878 --> 38:02.914
I just use the same one
every year.

38:02.947 --> 38:05.316
‐ Listen, I want to be
really clear with you.

38:05.350 --> 38:08.186
If you stay in line,
you're gonna get very rich,

38:08.219 --> 38:10.421
but if you fuck around‐‐
if you do anything

38:10.455 --> 38:13.324
to put any of my crew
in danger...

38:13.358 --> 38:15.760
I'll kill you.

38:15.794 --> 38:22.967
♪ ♪

38:23.001 --> 38:26.004
[indistinct chatter]

38:26.037 --> 38:29.340
[phones ringing]
[keys tapping]

38:29.374 --> 38:32.377
[computer whirring, chirping]

38:34.379 --> 38:37.348
[sped‐up audio whirring]

38:43.488 --> 38:46.524
[computer chirping]

38:48.259 --> 38:50.562
[foreboding music]

38:50.595 --> 38:52.597
[mouse clicks]

38:52.630 --> 38:54.265
♪ ♪

38:54.299 --> 38:56.601
[keys tap]
[computer chirping]

38:56.634 --> 39:02.540
♪ ♪

39:02.574 --> 39:05.543
[mouse clicking]

39:05.577 --> 39:12.584
♪ ♪

39:22.026 --> 39:24.229
[keypad beeps]

39:24.262 --> 39:27.899
[line trilling]

39:27.932 --> 39:30.869
♪ ♪

39:30.902 --> 39:32.470
‐ This is Detective Estrada.

39:32.503 --> 39:34.639
‐ Hi, Officer,
this is Esme Carmona.

39:34.672 --> 39:35.573
‐ [sighs]
What can I do for you?

39:35.607 --> 39:38.743
‐ Um, there's a problem
with the footage

39:38.776 --> 39:40.011
from Olivia's building.

39:40.044 --> 39:42.480
‐ Olivia's case
has been closed.

39:42.513 --> 39:44.215
[sinister music]

39:44.249 --> 39:45.450
‐ What?

39:45.483 --> 39:48.753
‐ The coroner ruled it
a suicide.

39:48.786 --> 39:50.588
‐ No, that's not right.

39:50.622 --> 39:52.590
‐ I know your sister
was troubled,

39:52.624 --> 39:56.027
so what happened today
may be hard for you to accept.

39:56.060 --> 39:57.695
♪ ♪

39:57.729 --> 39:59.364
‐ How do you know
about my sister?

39:59.397 --> 40:01.699
‐ The case is closed.
Thanks for your call.

40:01.733 --> 40:08.773
♪ ♪

40:19.751 --> 40:22.720
[indistinct chatter, laughter]

40:22.754 --> 40:25.723
[funky pop music playing
over speakers]

40:25.757 --> 40:32.797
♪ ♪

40:33.831 --> 40:36.768
[suspenseful music]

40:36.801 --> 40:42.874
♪ ♪

40:42.907 --> 40:45.877
[girls giggling, chattering]

40:45.910 --> 40:49.714
♪ ♪

40:49.747 --> 40:51.349
‐ All right, bye, y'all.
Happy Remembrance Day.

40:51.382 --> 40:52.517
‐ See you later.
‐ Bye.

40:52.550 --> 40:59.557
♪ ♪
